PR Title: Created initial wireframes for Home Page and Qualification Page
Author: S1.5
S1.5
Comment Bodies:
feel free to pick and choose updates to the sentences below to update the current list for the flow:

1. User begins on the Home page.
1. User views About page.
1. The user navigates to the Qualification page via the Navbar, where they initially view an empty table of Qualifications.
1. The user opens a "create" component to create a Java Qualification and receives a successful 200 HTTP 1. The response includes the newly created Java Qualification in JSON format.
1. The create component closes automatically, and the user is brought back to the Qualification page, where the Java Qualification now appears in the table.
1. The user clicks on the Java Qualification, causing the table item to expand and reveal the Qualification details, fetched through a GET 1. The details displayed include a table of Workers assigned to this Qualification, which is currently empty.
1. The user repeats the creation process for a Security Qualification.
1. This new Security Qualification appears in the table on the Qualification page, following another successful 200 HTTP response.
1. The user clicks on the Security Qualification, which collapses any previously expanded Qualification details and shows the details for 1. This detail view also shows an empty table of Workers.
1. The user attempts to create a qualification with an invalid name and receives a 400 HTTP response, with an error message explaining the invalid name issue.
1. Upon returning to the Qualifications table, the table remains unchanged as the invalid Qualification was not added.
1. The user successfully creates a third Qualification named Experience, which then appears on the Qualification page sorted alphabetically.
1. The user navigates to the Worker page using the Navbar and views an initially empty table of Workers.
1. The user creates a Worker named John Doe, who has the Java and Security Qualifications, receiving a 200 response with the details in JSON format.
1. After returning to the Worker page, the user now sees John Doe listed among the Workers.
1. Upon clicking on John Doe, the Worker details expand to show an empty table of Projects and the two assigned Qualifications: Java and Security Certified.
1. The user then attempts to create a Worker named Pax Shirone without any Qualifications, but receives a 400 response indicating that a Worker cannot be created without Qualifications.
1. The user returns to the Worker page, which still only lists John Doe.
1. The user navigates back to the Qualification page via the Navbar, where the three previously created Qualifications are visible.
1. Clicking on the Java Qualification now shows John Doe listed in the associated Workers.
1. Repeating this for the Security Qualification also shows John Doe listed.
1. Finally, viewing the details of the Experience Qualification reveals an empty Worker table, indicating no Workers have been assigned this Qualification yet.

PR Title: DTO mutable object exposure Spotbug issue
Author: S3.4
Comment Bodies:
@coreydc7 I am assigning this review to you, as you brought up this issue initially, so I figure you will know what I'm trying to address here.
Essentially, Spotbugs is saying that some of the getters in our DTO classes are exposing mutable objects, and the private variables could be changed in ways that we don't expect this way. I have tried to change all of getters in the DTO files where this is an issue with this PR. I have not touched any test files. 
Spotbugs is also complaining about the setter functions. I don't think we should address that.... The setters are public ways to change these private variables anyway, so I don't see how we could make it better. Open to pushback on that!
Spotbugs also has similar issues with some of our main class files.  I will open a separate issue for that. 
 I will watch for your feedback before plowing into these other changes.  | I guess that without doing any copying with the setter, the private variable could be affected by changes in the input variable, potentially bypassing the setter. PR Title: Update view company qualifications use case descriptions
Comment Bodies:
When a user clicks either sort by description or by worker count, does that also change which criteria the search bar matches? (i.e., if the user sorts by worker count, would typing "5" in the search bar filter to only qualifications with 5 workers assigned)

In either case, I think your graph is also missing a node after the user sort nodes where the system clears the search string

Everything else seems clean and useful to me | > When a user clicks either sort by description or by worker count, does that also change which criteria the search bar matches? (i.e., if the user sorts by worker count, would typing "5" in the search bar filter to only qualifications with 5 workers assigned)

I was thinking the search bar would match worker names and qualification names (e.g. "J" might match
```
[{
    "description": "Java",
    "workers": ["Ash"]
},{
    "description": "Python",
    "workers": ["James", "Alix"]
}]
```
), but I suppose if we can have the search string be parsed as an int then maybe it could also match qualifications with at least that many workers? Maybe certain strings are special cases like "5-", "10", "4+". But that would all be implementation details so I didn't include it in the diagram.

> In either case, I think your graph is also missing a node after the user sort nodes where the system clears the search string

I would argue that this is not what we want. What if a user enters a search string and gets a list of results (e.g. search for qualifications with the worker "Calvin"), and then they want to sort by the qualifications with the least number of workers to see what Calvin's most valuable skills are? | Unless the workers associated with each qualification appear on the main qualification page, I think it is unintuitive to match non-displayed worker names with the search bar (especially if the qualifications lists is 100s of qualifications long).

If you still disagree I will merge, and we can determine what works best during the actual implementation. | Merging because the worker names are displayed on the main qualification page in a dropdown. This doesn't seem like a big issue | Maybe we have a checkbox that toggles searching the workers in addition to the descriptions?

I don't like the company endpoint methods being part of RestController.  I think they deserve their own class; RestController shouldn't need to know internal details about Company.

Perhaps we should take inspiration from the implementation in cs414 where each request was its own class, serialized directly from the JSON, which all implement a buildResponse() method | > I don't like the company endpoint methods being part of RestController. I think they deserve their own class; RestController shouldn't need to know internal details about Company.
> 
> Perhaps we should take inspiration from the implementation in cs414 where each request was its own class, serialized directly from the JSON, which all implement a buildResponse() method

While I understand where you are coming from on breaking up the rest controller, the instructions for the assignment are pretty specific on how we are supposed to implement it:

1. Do not modify existing code.
2. Do not change exception handling.
3. Do not change logging.
4. Do not add public methods, exceptions, and classes. Only add private methods to the RestController.
5. Use the provided endpoints as a guide to implement all other endpoints.
6. Update the methods getQualifications() and getQualification(String description) to return the actual data from the company object.
7. If a request cannot be satisfied, throw an exception. The exception handler will take care of the rest.
8. GET requests do not have a body.
9. When returning a DTO object, all fields must be initialized with the proper values.
10. When receiving a DTO object as the body of a request, not all fields are initialized. This is specified below by ‚ÄúBody required fields‚Äù.
11. DTO objects may contain a string field that represents a Qualification, or a Worker, or a Project. The string should contain their description or name. Do not use the toString, nor the JSON representation.
